      <hedline>
        <hl1>Academia and Cuba</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Mark D Szuchman disputes notion, in May 13 Arts &amp; Ideas article, that scholars in South Florida would find travel to and from Cuba difficult; says Florida International University teachers and students regularly travel there to conduct work in libraries and archives</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the notion that university scholars in South Florida would find travel to and from Cuba difficult (Arts &amp; Ideas pages, May 13): the opposite is true.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the notion that university scholars in South Florida would find travel to and from Cuba difficult (Arts &amp; Ideas pages, May 13): the opposite is true.</p>
        <p>Faculty members and students in Florida International University's history department (in which I am a professor), along with those from other departments interested in Cuba, travel there regularly to conduct field work in libraries and archives, take part in professional meetings and exchange ideas, and carry out normal professional activities.</p>
        <p>The reason that Latin American history, including Cuban history, thrives here is simple: the faculty remains committed to the view of the university as a haven for advancing ideas within the tradition of civil exchange.</p>
        <p>MARK D. SZUCHMAN  Miami, May 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
